1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,300
I think it's really important,

2

00:00:02,300  -->  00:00:05,160
and this is common with not just linear regression,

3

00:00:05,160  -->  00:00:08,140
but with any statistical technique that you do.

4

00:00:08,140  -->  00:00:12,980
Being very hyper aware of all

5

00:00:12,980  -->  00:00:17,980
of the possible caveats of the analysis that you're doing is super important.

6

00:00:17,980  -->  00:00:20,360
Almost everything that we do in the real-world is

7

00:00:20,360  -->  00:00:23,740
just an estimation process with statistics, and therefore,

8

00:00:23,740  -->  00:00:29,340
there are plenty of ways that you can answer things incorrectly or do

9

00:00:29,340  -->  00:00:32,240
things wrong if you aren't aware of the assumptions or

10

00:00:32,240  -->  00:00:35,600
some of the things that are associated with whatever technique you use,

11

00:00:35,600  -->  00:00:37,260
whether that's a linear regression model,

12

00:00:37,260  -->  00:00:39,160
whether it's hypothesis testing,

13

00:00:39,160  -->  00:00:40,860
whether you're building confidence intervals,

14

00:00:40,860  -->  00:00:44,260
whether you're using really complex methods like Monte Carlo methods,

15

00:00:44,260  -->  00:00:46,405
or you're building really complex models like

16

00:00:46,405  -->  00:00:49,930
ensemble-based methods or deep neural networks,

17

00:00:49,930  -->  00:00:52,270
there are always assumptions being made.

18

00:00:52,270  -->  00:00:56,020
So being hyper aware of what those assumptions are,

19

00:00:56,020  -->  00:00:59,420
or some of the things that can go wrong with your analysis are

20

00:00:59,420  -->  00:01:02,855
super important to make sure that you don't just drive

21

00:01:02,855  -->  00:01:05,380
100% into some decision that has

22

00:01:05,380  -->  00:01:10,635
this loophole that you weren't aware of or has this assumption that you weren't aware of.

23

00:01:10,635  -->  00:01:15,620
I think, with really complex models,

24

00:01:15,620  -->  00:01:20,660
you almost need to be more afraid of overfitting into certain situations,

25

00:01:20,660  -->  00:01:24,085
and then thinking that's going to drive the right answer in every situation.

26

00:01:24,085  -->  00:01:27,780
Then with simpler modeling techniques like linear regression,

27

00:01:27,780  -->  00:01:31,460
you need to be more aware that the model is very simple,

28

00:01:31,460  -->  00:01:35,480
and therefore, might drive to conclusions that are oversimplified and that

29

00:01:35,480  -->  00:01:39,720
are not necessarily taking into account all of the complexities of the world.

30

00:01:39,720  -->  00:01:42,490
They're on the two extremes.
